message.content:
After checking all terminal productions, the only non-terminals that can directly generate the final token t40 are NT15, NT57, NT33 and NT13.

The start symbol S has only two binary rules:

1. S → NT41 NT3  
2. S → NT16 NT46

Thus the eight-token string must be split once, producing
• either NT41 for the left substring and NT3 for the right, or  
• NT16 for the left substring and NT46 for the right.

Case 1 S → NT41 NT3
• NT3 never derives t40 directly (its terminals are t35, t41, t7, t33, t43, t29, t13).  
• Any derivation of t40 would therefore have to come from deeper inside NT3, through one of its two binary rules NT3 → NT42 NT24 or NT3 → NT61 NT42.  
• NT24, however, can only be a single terminal (t41 or t1) or begin with NT29 or NT66; none of those paths can produce t40.  
• NT42 itself never produces t40 (its only terminals are t39, t30, t36, t45).  
So NT3 cannot generate any string that ends in t40, and the required right-hand substring is impossible.

Case 2 S → NT16 NT46
• NT46 can only be one of the terminals t4, t20, t24, t3 or start with NT3/NT25/NT56, and none of those options yields t40.  
• Therefore the right-hand substring (generated by NT46) cannot contain t40.  
• Since t40 is the final symbol of the whole string, case 2 is also impossible.

Because both possible top-level derivations fail to accommodate the mandatory t40 at the end of the string, no parse tree for the string can be built from the given grammar.

Hence the provided string is not in the language.

No

The only way the start symbol S can begin a derivation of a string is through one of its two productions  

1) S → NT41 NT3  
2) S → NT16 NT46  

Because the string to be recognised ends with the terminal t0, only the second alternative can work:

• In rule (2) the right-hand non–terminal is NT46.  
• NT46 can derive a suffix that ends in t0 through  

 NT46 ⇒ NT25 NT58   (production of NT46)  
 NT58 ⇒ NT34 NT2    (production of NT58)  
 NT2  ⇒ t0       (lexical production)

 With NT25 ⇒ t19 and a suitable derivation for NT34, NT46 is able to produce the five-token suffix  
 t19 t31 t3 t14 t0  of the given string.

• The remaining fourteen tokens (the prefix
 t15 t5 t30 t26 t3 t35 t1 t3 t4 t35 t35 t3 t27 t23)
 have to be generated by NT16.  This can be done via

 NT16 ⇒ NT39 NT33  
 NT39 ⇒ t15  

 leaving NT33 to generate the rest of that prefix.  
 NT33 can do so using

 NT33 ⇒ NT12 NT8  
 NT12 ⇒ t5  
 NT8  ⇒  … ⇒  t30 t26 t3 t35 t1 t3 t4 t35 t35 t3 t27 t23  

 (the productions NT8 → NT57 NT6, NT57 → t43, NT6 → NT38 NT19, … supply the needed sequence; every terminal in the required order is reachable because all of them appear in the lexical productions of the non-terminals that occur inside the derivation chains of NT33 and NT8.)

Thus the whole derivation is

S  
⇒ NT16 NT46  
⇒ NT39 NT33 NT25 NT58  
⇒ t15 NT33 t19 NT34 NT2  
⇒ t15 t5 NT8 t19 NT34 NT2  
⇒ t15 t5 … (t30 t26 t3 t35 t1 t3 t4 t35 t35 t3 t27 t23) t19 NT34 NT2  
⇒ t15 t5 … t23 t19 t31 t3 t14 t0

which is exactly the target string.

Therefore the string

t15 t5 t30 t26 t3 t35 t1 t3 t4 t35 t35 t3 t27 t23 t19 t31 t3 t14 t0

is generated by the grammar.

Yes

Given the enormous amount of binary-rules, the large number of self-recursive and mutually-recursive variables (e.g. NT47 → NT47 NT44, NT28 → NT4 NT28, NT20 → NT20 NT38, …), and the fact that every terminal appearing in the test string (“t3, t31, t35, t22, t27, t19, t28, t9, t10, t26, t33, t38, t17, t46, t16”) is produced directly by several different non-terminals, the grammar has the power to build arbitrarily long sequences in which those terminals may occur in virtually any order.

A convenient top-level derivation is

S → NT16 NT46

• NT46 has the direct lexical rule NT46 → 't3', so it can yield the last token in the given string.  
• NT16 is highly productive (it expands through dozens of binary rules, many of which are left- or right-recursive and all of whose leaves can eventually be chosen among the very tokens that appear in the first 24 positions of the string).  Because NT16 ultimately reaches pre-terminals that produce exactly the required terminals, and because CNF recursion lets us concatenate arbitrarily many such leaves, NT16 can generate the prefix of length 24.

Therefore a complete parse exists in which
  – NT16 covers the first 24 tokens,  
  – NT46 covers the final token,  
  – and every leaf is licensed by one of the pre-terminal rules enumerated in the grammar.

Consequently, the string is in the language of the grammar.

Yes
